elements.content: Hydro/solvothermal and bilayered-diffusion methods using pyridine (py), 3-methylpyridine (3-mpy), and 4-methylpyridine (4-mpy) as weak bases and small terminal ligands generated seven CoII, MnII, and NiII two-dimensional (2D) coordination polymers with di-, trinuclear metal clusters as secondary building units (SBUs) from an organic bridging ligand, 1,1′-biphenyl-3,3′-dicarboxylic acid (H2 L). Coordination polymers based on trinuclear SBUs are {[Co3(L)3(py)2](py)} n (1) and [Mn3(L)3(py)2(H2O)2] n (4), and those based on dinuclear SBUs are {[Co2(L)2(py)3(H2O)2](py)(CH3OH)} n (2), [Ni2(L)2(py)4(H2O)] n (3), {[Mn2(L)2(py)3(H2O)2](py)2(CH3CH2OH)} n (5), {[Mn2(L)2(3-mpy)4(H2O)](CH3OH)0.5} n (6), and [Mn2(L)2(4-mpy)2] n (7). Further structural analysis indicates that 1, 4, and 7 have a (4,4) grid layered structure and 2, 3, 5, and 6 possess a (3,6) sheet structure. Magnetization studies show the existence of ferromagnetic coupling for 1 with a positive zJ value of 0.97 cm–1, weak antiferromagnetic coupling for 2 (−E 2/k = −4.6 K), very weak antiferromagnetic coupling for 3 with a small negative J value of −0.17 cm–1, weak or medium antiferromagnetic couplings for 4, 5, and 6 with the negative J values of −1.17, −1.53, and −1.62 cm–1, respectively, and very strong antiferromagnetic coupling for 7 with a very large negative J value of −16.62 cm–1.

elements.clean_text:
Introduction

The design and construction of secondary building units (SBUs) with novel structures and various connections in coordination chemistry have attracted more attention. On one hand, metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) based on SBUs are of significance not only for their fascinating structures (topologies) but also for special functional material purposes, such as gas adsorption, catalysts, and luminescence. On the other hand, SBUs containing transitional metals afford more possibilities in molecule magnets, including single-molecule magnets (SMM), single chains magnets (SCM), spin crossover (SCO), and spin canting (SC) magnetizms. Although research and review papers have reported large amount of coordination compounds constructed by various SBUs and concluded some rules to set up desired SBUs, detailed studies on the effect factors of SBUs are still limited.

elements.content: Multifunctional bridges such as carboxylates have been utilized in the formation of rigid MOFs via reticular synthesis due to their ability to aggregate metal ions into neutral clusters, which is SBUs. Monocarboxyl bridging ligands and multicarboxyl acids can both be used to construct SBUs via carboxyl O atoms and carboxyl groups as bridges when bases are present during the reaction. The structural natures of SBUs are diverse depending on the metal ions, pH, solvents, the secondary ligands and/or terminal ligands, synthetic methods, etc. Pyridine, as an usual organic solvent and a weak organic base, can both tune the pH of synthetic systems and act as small terminal ligands for SBUs. However, other derivatives of pyridine, such as 3- and 4-methyl pyridine, are seldom used in the construction of SBUs. In view of the reported work on the constructions of MOFs and our previous research, we predict that the above-mentioned pyridyl compounds can be used to tune the construction of SBUs. To investigate this idea, we selected a dicarboxyl organic acid, 1,1′-biphenyl-3,3′-dicarboxylic acid (H2 L), which was reported possessing two types of conformation and a few bridging modes in the literature, to construct coordination compounds with SBUs in the presence of these pyridine derivatives.

Experimental Section

Materials and Physical Measurements

All reagents and solvents were commercially available. Infrared spectra were recorded on a FTS-40 infrared spectrometer as KBr pellets. Elemental analyses were performed on a Flash EA 1112 analyzer. The variable-temperature magnetic susceptibilities were measured on polycrystalline samples with a Quantum Design MPMS SQUID susceptometer operating at a magnetic field of 0.1 T in a temperature range of 1.8 (or 2)-300 K. The diamagnetism of all samples and sample holders were taken into account.

elements.content: The procedure and condition used to synthesize compounds 2, 5–7 are as follows: A solution of metal salts (0.1 mmol) [Co(NO3)2·6H2O for 2, MnCl2·4H2O for 5–7] in methanol (ethanol for 5) (10 cm3) was carefully layered on a solution of H2 L (0.1 mmol) in the water/pyridine (3-methylpyridine for 6, 4-methylpyridine for 7) (10 cm3/1.4 cm3) in a capped straight glass tube. Synthesis and Coordination Modes of H2L

Ligand H2 L was doubly deprotonated in the construction of all coordination polymers and presents four coordination modes and two types of conformation (Scheme ). Five types of di- and trinuclear SBUs were constructed through the aqueous oxygen atoms, carboxyl oxygen atoms, and carboxyl groups as bridges (Scheme ). In all compounds, ligand L also acts as nearly linear spacers to connect SBUs, forming three types of 2D nets. Interestingly, the SBUs are sensitive to synthetic methods and terminal ligands. For Co and Mn coordination polymers, dimeric SBUs were constructed by two-layer diffusion for 2, 5, 6, and 7, while trimeric SBUs were assembled by solvent/hydrothermal methods for 1 and 4. On the other hand, when 4-methylpridine was used as a terminal ligand, the paddlewheel dimeric SBU was formed for 7; however, another type of dimeric SBU was formed for 6 when 3-methylpyridine was used as terminal ligands under the same synthetic system.

Each SBU (Scheme , type c) contains three Co atoms in one line, including two symmetry-related Co atoms. The Co1 atom in the center position is in a slightly distorted octahedral coordination environment in which four symmetry-related carboxyl oxygen atoms of four distinct L ligands are located in the equatorial positions and two symmetry-related oxygen atoms of two distinct L ligands in the apical position (Figure ). The cis bond angles around this metal center range from ca. 87.25(6) to 92.75(6)°. The other two symmetry-related Co atoms (Co2 and Co2A) on the side positions are coordinated by two O atoms of one carboxyl group, two O atoms of two distinct carboxyl groups from two L ligands, and one N atom from one pyridine terminal ligand, defining a distorted trigonal bipyramidal coordination environment (confirmed by τ). The largest and the smallest cis bond angles around the side metal centers are ca. 119.83(6) and 59.61(5)°, respectively. The central and one side Co atoms in one SBU are bridged by two carboxyl groups in bidentate mode and one carboxyl group in bridging chelate mode with the Co···Co separation of ca. 3.173 Å. The Co–O bond distances are in the range of ca. 1.984(2)–2.336(2) Å, which are comparable with the reported ones.

Magnetic Properties

The magnetic properties of compounds 1, 3, 4, and 5 have been investigated over the temperature range of 1.8-300 K and the other three compounds have been investigated over the temperature range of 2-300 K at the applied field of 1000 G.

elements.content: For 1, as shown in Figure , the χM T product of each Co3 unit (8.09 cm3 K mol–1) at 300 K is larger than that (5.63 cm3 K mol–1) expected for three magnetically isolated high-spin CoII ions with S = 3/2, revealing a significant orbital contribution as also found in other high spin Co complexes. By cooling the temperature, the χM T value decreases until a minimum (7.06 cm3 K mol–1) at T min = 35 K. The magnetic susceptibility from 50 to 300 K obeys the Curie–Weiss law with a Weiss constant θ of −10.47 K and a Curie constant C of 8.40 cm3 K mol–1 (). Upon lowering of the temperature to 4.5 K, χM T abruptly increases to a maximum (8.10 cm3 K mol–1). Below 4.5 K, the χM T has a rapid drop, which may to attributed to the magnetic field saturation effect and/or antiferromagnetic interaction between the layers. The magnetic behaviors of this compound are further characterized by field-dependent magnetization measurements in the low-temperature region. As shown in Figure , the isotherm magnetizations at 1.8 and 5 K clearly display a drastic rise in M vs H below 10 kGauss, and then slowly increase in high-field region and do not saturate. The experimentally observed magnetization at the applied field of 70 kGauss at 1.8 K is about 6.2 Nβ per Co3 unit, which is smaller than the value of 9.0 Nβ anticipated for three independent CoII with S = 3/2 ground state, but larger than those values usually less than 4.0 Nβ for antiferromagnetic interactions within trimeric Co(II) units. It should be noted that magnetic research for high spin Co system is fairly complicated and difficult because many factors, especially the strong spin–orbital coupling, can influence the magnetic behavior. The first decrease for χM T value (300–35 K) and the not large negative θ value may be mainly due to the strong spin–orbital coupling of the single-ion behavior at high temperature. The χM T abrupt increase (35–4.5 K) can be interpreted by ferromagnetic coupling interactions within the trimeric unit, which is strong enough to compensate for the single-ion behavior resulting from spin–orbital coupling. This can also be confirmed by the slow increase of magnetization at high fields and large magnetization values at the applied field of 70 kG at both 1.8 and 5 K.

elements.content: The main magnetic exchange pathway is the exchange between neighboring trimeric Co(II) ions to the μ2-Ocarboxyl bridge with the superexchange angle Co–Ocarboxyl–Co of 97.16(6)°. Although such an angle is significantly larger than the standard angle (90°) used to judge the ferromagnetic interactions from the Goodenough-Kanamori rules, it is much smaller than those reported superexchange angles generally around 110° for similar multinuclear Co(II) compounds with the Co–O–Co magnetic exchange pathway. This is consistent with the fact that the smaller angle would increase the ferromagnetic contribution or the complex with the smaller angle showed the ferromagnetic interaction. There are other possible antiferromagnetic pathways, such as carboxyl bridges (Co–OCO–Co) within trimeric units and the organic ligand bridges between trimeric units. But they are very weak due to the much long magnetic pathway or much longer Co(II)···Co(II) distance.

elements.content: For 2, the χM at 35–300 K displays continuous slow increase with a decrease of temperature and then sharply increase when lowering the temperature from 35 to 5 K. Below 5 K, there is a clear decrease of the χM values. The presence of the maximum χM value gives a signal of an antiferromagnetic interaction within the dimeric CoII ions. The maximum χM value is 0.365 cm3 mol–1 at 5 K (Figure ). The critical temperature T N = 3.1 K determined by the peak of d(χT)/dT is very low. The χM T value of 6.46 cm3 K mol–1 per Co2 unit at 300 K is much larger than that (3.76 cm3 K mol–1) expected for two magnetically isolated high-spin CoII ions with S = 3/2, revealing a significant orbital contribution. Upon lowering the temperature, the χM T value first slowly decreases to about 20 K and then rapidly decreases to a value of 0.56 cm3 K mol–1 at 2 K (Figure ). The magnetic susceptibility from 50 to 300 K obeys the Curie–Weiss law with a Weiss constant θ of −14.5 K and a Curie constant C of 6.87 cm3 K mol–1 (). The decrease of the χM T value or the negative θ value can be induced by antiferromagnetic coupling interactions within and between dimeric units as well as strong spin–orbit coupling. According to the Goodenough–Kanamori rules and structural parameters, two possible magnetic exchange pathways can be defined. The first and strongest is the exchange between dimeric Co(II) ions to the carboxyl bridges (Co–OCO–Co) and μ2–OH2 water bridge with the exchange angle Co–Oaq–Co at 111.26(8)°, which is near to 120° and significantly larger than 90°, usually leading to strong antiferromagnetic interaction. This is consistent with the observed negative Weiss temperature (θ = −14.5 K). The second is the exchange between the dimeric units via the dicarboxyl ligand bridges with a Co(II)···Co(II) distance of ca. 9.784 Å, which could be weakly antiferromagnetic.

elements.content: Compounds 5 and 6 contain the same Mn2 magnetic exchange unit and similar molecular structure. So their magnetic behaviors are also similar. Curves of χM T versus T and χM versus T for these two compounds are shown in Figure and . At 300 K, the χM T values for 5 and 6 are 8.17 and 8.01 cm3 K mol–1, respectively, which are somewhat lower than that expected for two noninteracting MnII ions (8.75 cm3 K mol–1). For both compounds, χM T continuously decreases upon cooling and reaches a value of 0.21 cm3 K mol–1 at 1.8 K for 5 and of 0.23 cm3 K mol–1 at 2 K for 6. This behavior is characteristic of an antiferromagnetic interaction between two high-spin MnII ions. The presence of a χM maximum of 0.18 cm3 mol–1 at 14 K for both compounds is the signature of an antiferromagnetic interaction with a singlet ground state. At 2 K, the χM values for both compounds are very near to 0.12 cm3 mol–1, which are 2/3 of the values at T max. The critical temperatures T N = 8 K for 4 and 9.2 K for 5 are determined by the peak of d(χT)/dT. The magnetic data for χM were treated by the isotropic Heisenberg S 1 = S 2 = 5/2 spin-coupled dimer model (Ĥ = −2JŜ1·Ŝ 2) considering interdimer magnetic exchange (J′) within the layer (see , eq 3). The best fitting parameters are J = −1.53 cm–1, J′ = −0.56 cm–1, g = 2.06, and R = 3.1 × 10–6 for 5, and J = −1.62 cm–1, J′ = −0.33 cm–1, g = 2.02, and R = 1.7 × 10–6 for 6. These negative J and J′ values indicating weak antiferromagnetic exchange interactions and g values are comparable with those found in other reported dimer MnII systems. The magnetic susceptibilities for these two compounds both obey the Curie–Weiss law and plots of 1/χM versus T yield straight lines () with C = 9.00 cm3 K mol–1, θ = −24.9 K (30–300 K) for 5 and C = 8.50 cm3 K mol–1, θ = −15.1 K (50–300 K) for 6. These negative Weiss constants θ further suggest antiferromagnetic interactions between two MnII ions. It is worth noting that antiferromagnetic interactions between two MnII ions within a dimer indicated by the negative J values (−1.53 and −1.62 cm–1) for 5 and 6 are significantly stronger than that between two neighboring MnII ions within a trimer indicated by the smaller negative J value (−1.17 cm–1) for 4. This may be caused by the different exchange angles of magnetic exchange pathways. The Mn–O–Mn angles of 107.08(9) and 106.74(8)° for 5 and 6 are larger than that [102.04(6)°] of 4. This tendency is somewhat consistent with the correlation rules between the value of −J and metal-O-metal bridge angle for Cu(II) and Ni(II) complexes found by Hatfield and Nag, respectively.

elements.content: One complex with paddlewheel binuclear MnII SBUs bridged by carboxyl groups was reported by Fu etc., but unfortunately the magnetic property of this compound was not investigated. Amount of complexes with paddlewheel binuclear CuII SBUs and their magnetic properties have been reported. Strong antiferromagnetic exchanges with large negative J values (intradimer coupling constant) have been found for almost all reported complexes with such paddlewheel binuclear CuII SBUs with very short Cu···Cu separations. Thus, magnetic exchange interactions within two dimeric MnII ions with very short Mn···Mn separation for 7 may be strong antiferromagnetic exchanges, compared to that of the above two complexes with dimeric MnII SBUs. As shown in Figure , the χM T product of each Mn2 unit (5.31 cm3 K mol–1) at 300 K is very lower than that (8.75 cm3 K mol–1) expected for two magnetically isolated high-spin MnII ions with S = 5/2. On cooling, χM T decreases rapidly down to 0.184 cm3 K mol–1 at 2 K, indicative of strong antiferromagnetic coupling across the Mn2 paddle-wheel dinuclear units. The magnetic susceptibility data were fit to the above-mentioned expression (see , eq 3) for a MnII dimer of spin S = 5/2 ions, with best fit parameters of J = −16.62 cm–1, J′ = −0.78 cm–1, g = 2.09, and R = 2.5 × 10–4 above 50 K. The negative J value for 7 is very larger than those for 5 and 6, indicating very strong antiferromagnetic coupling attributing to too short Mn···Mn distance within the paddle-wheel dinuclear unit.

elements.content: To conclude the magnetic properties of these 2D coordination polymers with dimeric or trimeric SBUs by comparing the above magnetic behaviors, especially the magnetic exchange coupling parameters, the intra-SBU magnetic pathways are dominant because the J values are significantly larger than the J′ values through best fits for compounds 3–7. This conclusion is also consistent with magnetism-related structural analysis of SBUs and 2D frameworks, including the exchange angles of magnetic exchange pathways and metal···metal separations. Larger exchange angles and very shorter metal···metal separations within SBUs can both lead to strong antiferromagnetic coupling interactions. Therefore, the systematic setup of SBUs with structural diversities would be of significance to the synthesis of magnetic materials and the analyses of magnetic behaviors for coordination polymers and/or metal–organic frameworks.

Conclusion

We have systematically synthesized and structurally characterized seven new 2D coordination polymers using one dicarboxyl acid as bridging ligand and three pyridyl compounds as terminal ligands and weak bases with three transitional metal salts. Different di/trinuclear SBUs linked by carboxyl groups and water molecules as bridges have been assembled through different synthetic methods and tuned by different terminal ligands. The structural diversity of SBUs brings about different magnetic behaviors in these compounds.

For 1, as shown in Figure , the χM T product of each Co3 unit (8.09 cm3 K mol–1) at 300 K is larger than that (5.63 cm3 K mol–1) expected for three magnetically isolated high-spin CoII ions with S = 3/2, revealing a significant orbital contribution as also found in other high spin Co complexes. By cooling the temperature, the χM T value decreases until a minimum (7.06 cm3 K mol–1) at T min = 35 K. The magnetic susceptibility from 50 to 300 K obeys the Curie–Weiss law with a Weiss constant θ of −10.47 K and a Curie constant C of 8.40 cm3 K mol–1 (). Upon lowering of the temperature to 4.5 K, χM T abruptly increases to a maximum (8.10 cm3 K mol–1). Below 4.5 K, the χM T has a rapid drop, which may to attributed to the magnetic field saturation effect and/or antiferromagnetic interaction between the layers. The magnetic behaviors of this compound are further characterized by field-dependent magnetization measurements in the low-temperature region. As shown in Figure , the isotherm magnetizations at 1.8 and 5 K clearly display a drastic rise in M vs H below 10 kGauss, and then slowly increase in high-field region and do not saturate. The experimentally observed magnetization at the applied field of 70 kGauss at 1.8 K is about 6.2 Nβ per Co3 unit, which is smaller than the value of 9.0 Nβ anticipated for three independent CoII with S = 3/2 ground state, but larger than those values usually less than 4.0 Nβ for antiferromagnetic interactions within trimeric Co(II) units. It should be noted that magnetic research for high spin Co system is fairly complicated and difficult because many factors, especially the strong spin–orbital coupling, can influence the magnetic behavior. The first decrease for χM T value (300–35 K) and the not large negative θ value may be mainly due to the strong spin–orbital coupling of the single-ion behavior at high temperature. The χM T abrupt increase (35–4.5 K) can be interpreted by ferromagnetic coupling interactions within the trimeric unit, which is strong enough to compensate for the single-ion behavior resulting from spin–orbital coupling. This can also be confirmed by the slow increase of magnetization at high fields and large magnetization values at the applied field of 70 kG at both 1.8 and 5 K.
